          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search          For the British film and television director, see Ian Sharp. Iain Sharp, born in 1953, is a New Zealand poet and critic. Biography[edit] Born in Glasgow in 1953, Sharp emigrated with his family to New Zealand in 1961, where they settled in Auckland. He studied at Auckland University where he received a doctorate in English in 1982. Soon after he qualified as a librarian from the New Zealand Library School.[1] He currently works part-time in the Special Collections Department of Auckland Central City Library, and is also a reviewer, critic and columnist for the New Zealand Listener magazine.[2] Works[edit]  Why Mammals Shiver, Auckland: One Eyed Press, 1981 She Is Trying to Kidnap the Blind Person, Auckland: Hard Echo Press, 1985 The Pierrot Variations, Auckland: Hard Echo Press, 1985 Two Poets: Selections from the Work of Suzanne Chapman and Iain Sharp, edited by Suzanne Chapman, Auckland: Auckland English Association, 1985 The Singing Harp, Paekakariki: Earl of Seacliff Art Workshop, 2004 Real Gold: treasures of Auckland City Libraries, text by Iain Sharp; photographs by Haruhiko Sameshima, Auckland University Press, 2007 Our Favourite Poems: New Zealanders choose their best-loved poems, introduction by Iain Sharp, Craig Potton Publishing, 2007, ISBN 9781877333682 Heaphy: Explorer, Artist, Settler, Auckland University Press, 2008 Sharing Our Ghosts, Poems by Joy MacKenzie & Iain Sharp, Auckland: Cumberland Press, 2011  References[edit]   ^ Anthology of New Zealand Poetry in English, Oxford University Press, 1997 ^ The Oxford Companion to New Zealand Literature, edited by Roger Robinson and Nelson Wattie (1998). Sharp, Iain at New Zealand Book Council        Authority control    WorldCat Identities VIAF: 86102381 ISNI: 0000 0000 8161 301X SUDOC: 154185698             This article about a New Zealand writer or poet is a stub. You can help Wikipedia